  "text": "Comprehensive ACL Authorization Implementation in Apache Kafka\n\nFound 21 Java source files in clients/src/main containing Access Control List (ACL) authorization and related logic:\n\nCore Authorization Interfaces and Classes:\n1. Authorizer (interface) - Main pluggable authorizer interface for Kafka brokers, defines methods for authorization, ACL creation/deletion, and ACL retrieval\n2. AuthorizerServerInfo (interface) - Runtime broker configuration metadata provided to authorizers during startup\n\nAuthorization Support Classes:\n3. AuthorizerNotReadyException - Exception indicating authorizer is not ready to receive requests\n4. AclCreateResult - Result class for ACL creation operations\n5. AclDeleteResult - Result class for ACL deletion operations with detailed binding delete results\n\nACL Data Models:\n6. AclBinding - Represents binding between resource pattern and access control entry\n7. AclBindingFilter - Filter for matching AclBinding objects\n8. AclOperation - Enum representing ACL operations (READ, WRITE, CREATE, DELETE, ALTER, DESCRIBE, CLUSTER_ACTION, DESCRIBE_CONFIGS, ALTER_CONFIGS, IDEMPOTENT_WRITE, ALL)\n9. AclPermissionType - Enum representing ACL permission types (ALLOW, DENY)\n\nAdmin Client API Classes:\n10. CreateAclsOptions - Client options for creating ACLs\n11. CreateAclsResult - Result of create ACLs operation\n12. DeleteAclsOptions - Client options for deleting ACLs\n13. DeleteAclsResult - Result of delete ACLs operation\n14. DescribeAclsOptions - Client options for describing ACLs\n15. DescribeAclsResult - Result of describe ACLs operation\n\nKafka Protocol Request/Response Classes:\n16. CreateAclsRequest - Protocol request for creating ACLs\n17. CreateAclsResponse - Protocol response for create ACLs\n18. DeleteAclsRequest - Protocol request for deleting ACLs\n19. DeleteAclsResponse - Protocol response for delete ACLs\n20. DescribeAclsRequest - Protocol request for describing ACLs\n21. DescribeAclsResponse - Protocol response for describe ACLs\n\nKey Findings:\n- No Authorizer implementations found in core/src/main/ or clients/src/main/ directories\n- All interface definitions and supporting classes are in clients/src/main/, allowing for pluggable authorizer implementations\n- Authorizer interface provides async ACL update methods and synchronous authorization checks\n- Complete separation between interface (clients module) and implementations (likely in separate modules)"
